    },\r\n    {\r\n      \"id\": 234343028,\r\n      \"plant_name\": \"Allium fistulosum\",\r\n      \"plant_details\": {\r\n        \"common_names\": [\r\n          \"Welsh onion\",\r\n          \"bunching onion\",\r\n          \"green onion\",\r\n          \"long green onion\",\r\n          \"Japanese bunching onion\",\r\n          \"spring onion\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allium_fistulosum\",\r\n        \"name_authority\": \"Allium fistulosum L.\",\r\n        \"wiki_description\": {\r\n          \"value\": \"Allium fistulosum, the Welsh onion, also commonly called bunching onion, long green onion, Japanese bunching onion, and spring onion, is a species of perennial plant, often considered to be a kind of scallion.\\nThe species is very similar in taste and odor to the related common onion, Allium cepa, and hybrids between the two (tree onions) exist. A. fistulosum, however, does not develop bulbs, and possesses hollow leaves (fistulosum means \\\"hollow\\\") and scapes. Larger varieties of the A. fistulosum resemble the leek, such as the Japanese negi, whilst smaller varieties resemble chives. A. fistulosum can multiply by forming perennial evergreen clumps. It is also grown in a bunch as an ornamental plant.\",\r\n          \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allium_fistulosum\",\r\n          \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\",\r\n          \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"\r\n        },\r\n        \"taxonomy\": {\r\n          \"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\",\r\n          \"family\": \"Amaryllidaceae\",\r\n          \"genus\": \"Allium\",\r\n          \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\",\r\n          \"order\": \"Asparagales\",\r\n          \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"\r\n        },\r\n        \"synonyms\": [\r\n          \"Allium bouddae\",\r\n          \"Allium kashgaricum\",\r\n          \"Cepa fissilis\",\r\n          \"Cepa fistulosa\",\r\n          \"Cepa ventricosa\",\r\n          \"Kepa fistulosa\",\r\n          \"Phyllodolon fistulosum\",\r\n          \"Porrum fistulosum\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"scientific_name\": \"Allium fistulosum\",\r\n        \"structured_name\": {\r\n          \"genus\": \"allium\",\r\n          \"species\": \"fistulosum\"\r\n        }\r\n      },\r\n      \"probability\": 0.03688405608686612,\r\n      \"confirmed\": false,\r\n      \"similar_images\": [\r\n        {\r\n          \"id\": \"a77a8687f6b52abf887f054baf3daa49\",\r\n          \"similarity\": 0.3662875081084549,\r\n          \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/a77/a8687f6b52abf887f054baf3daa49.jpg\",\r\n          \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/a77/a8687f6b52abf887f054baf3daa49.small.jpg\"\r\n        },\r\n        {\r\n          \"id\": \"3dee9dcef7c82f16068ae96e232c8378\",\r\n          \"similarity\": 0.15926277607004458,\r\n          \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/3de/e9dcef7c82f16068ae96e232c8378.jpg\",\r\n          \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/3de/e9dcef7c82f16068ae96e232c8378.small.jpg\",\r\n          \"citation\": \"Jan Su00f8rensen\",\r\n          \"license_name\": \"CC BY 4.0\",\r\n          \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\"\r\n        }\r\n      ]\r\n    },\r\n    {\r\n      \"id\": 234343029,\r\n      \"plant_name\": \"Narcissus\",\r\n      \"plant_details\": {\r\n        \"common_names\": [\r\n          \"daffodil\",\r\n          \"jonquil\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narcissus_(plant)\",\r\n        \"name_authority\": \"Narcissus L.\",\r\n        \"wiki_description\": {\r\n          \"value\": \"Narcissus is a genus of predominantly spring flowering perennial plants of the amaryllis family, Amaryllidaceae. Various common names including daffodil, narcissus and jonquil are used to describe all or some members of the genus. Narcissus has conspicuous flowers with six petal-like tepals surmounted by a cup- or trumpet-shaped corona. The flowers are generally white or yellow (also orange or pink in garden varieties), with either uniform or contrasting coloured tepals and corona.\\nNarcissus were well known in ancient civilisation, both medicinally and botanically, but formally described by Linnaeus in his Species Plantarum (1753). The genus is generally considered to have about ten sections with approximately 50 species. The number of species has varied, depending on how they are classified, due to similarity between species and hybridisation. The genus arose some time in the Late Oligocene to Early Miocene epochs, in the Iberian peninsula and adjacent areas of southwest Europe. The exact origin of the name Narcissus is unknown, but it is often linked to a Greek word for intoxicated (narcotic) and the myth of the youth of that name who fell in love with his own reflection. The English word \\\"daffodil\\\" appears to be derived from \\\"asphodel\\\", with which it was commonly compared.\\nThe species are native to meadows and woods in southern Europe and North Africa with a centre of diversity in the Western Mediterranean, particularly the Iberian peninsula. Both wild and cultivated plants have naturalised widely, and were introduced into the Far East prior to the tenth century. Narcissi tend to be long-lived bulbs, which propagate by division, but are also insect-pollinated. Known pests, diseases and disorders include viruses, fungi, the larvae of flies, mites and nematodes. Some Narcissus species have become extinct, while others are threatened by increasing urbanisation and tourism.\\nHistorical accounts suggest narcissi have been cultivated from the earliest times, but became increasingly popular in Europe after the 16th century and by the late 19th century were an important commercial crop centred primarily in the Netherlands. Today narcissi are popular as cut flowers and as ornamental plants in private and public gardens. The long history of breeding has resulted in thousands of different cultivars. For horticultural purposes, narcissi are classified into divisions, covering a wide range of shapes and colours. Like other members of their family, narcissi produce a number of different alkaloids, which provide some protection for the plant, but may be poisonous if accidentally ingested. This property has been exploited for medicinal use in traditional healing and has resulted in the production of galantamine for the treatment of Alzheimers dementia. Long celebrated in art and literature, narcissi are associated with a number of themes in different cultures, ranging from death to good fortune, and as symbols of spring. The daffodil is the national flower of Wales and the symbol of cancer charities in many countries. The appearance of the wild flowers in spring is associated with festivals in many places.\",\r\n          \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narcissus_(plant)\",\r\n          \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\",\r\n          \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"\r\n        },\r\n        \"taxonomy\": {\r\n          \"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\",\r\n          \"family\": \"Amaryllidaceae\",\r\n          \"genus\": \"Narcissus\",\r\n          \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\",\r\n          \"order\": \"Asparagales\",\r\n          \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"\r\n        },\r\n        \"synonyms\": [\r\n          \"Ajax\",\r\n          \"Argenope\",\r\n          \"Assaracus\",\r\n          \"Aurelia\",\r\n          \"Autogenes\",\r\n          \"Braxireon\",\r\n          \"Calathinus\",\r\n          \"Carregnoa\",\r\n          \"Chione\",\r\n          \"Chloraster\",\r\n          \"Codiaminum\",\r\n          \"Corbularia\",\r\n          \"Cydenis\",\r\n          \"Diomedes\",\r\n          \"Ganymedes\",\r\n          \"Gymnoterpe\",\r\n          \"Helena\",\r\n          \"Hermione\",\r\n          \"Illus\",\r\n          \"Jonquilla\",\r\n          \"Moskerion\",\r\n          \"Oileus\",\r\n          \"Panza\",\r\n          \"Patrocles\",\r\n          \"Philogyne\",\r\n          \"Phylogyne\",\r\n          \"Plateana\",\r\n          \"Prasiteles\",\r\n          \"Queltia\",\r\n          \"Schisanthes\",\r\n          \"Stephanophorum\",\r\n          \"Tapeinaegle\",\r\n          \"Tapeinanthus\",\r\n          \"Tityrus\",\r\n          \"Tros\",\r\n          \"Veniera\",\r\n          \"u00d7 Narcibularia\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"scientific_name\": \"Narcissus\",\r\n        \"structured_name\": {\r\n          \"genus\": \"narcissus\"\r\n        }\r\n      },\r\n      \"probability\": 0.024087714861157787,\r\n      \"confirmed\": false,\r\n      \"similar_images\": [\r\n        {\r\n          \"id\": \"224257d4be9f982e8462b4a6438389a8\",\r\n          \"similarity\": 0.26959919103864893,\r\n          \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/224/257d4be9f982e8462b4a6438389a8.jpg\",\r\n          \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/224/257d4be9f982e8462b4a6438389a8.small.jpg\"\r\n        },\r\n        {\r\n          \"id\": \"55170d648a762be75648fdfaab896917\",\r\n          \"similarity\": 0.17466023284879884,\r\n          \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/551/70d648a762be75648fdfaab896917.jpg\",\r\n          \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/551/70d648a762be75648fdfaab896917.small.jpg\"\r\n        }\r\n      ]\r\n    },\r\n    {\r\n      \"id\": 234343030,\r\n      \"plant_name\": \"Hyacinthus orientalis\",\r\n      \"plant_details\": {\r\n        \"common_names\": [\r\n          \"common hyacinth\",\r\n          \"garden hyacinth\",\r\n          \"Dutch hyacinth\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyacinthus_orientalis\",\r\n        \"name_authority\": \"Hyacinthus orientalis L.\",\r\n        \"wiki_description\": {\r\n          \"value\": \"Hyacinthus orientalis, the common hyacinth, garden hyacinth or Dutch hyacinth, is a species of flowering plant in the family Asparagaceae, subfamily Scilloidiae, native to southwestern Asia, southern and central Turkey, northwestern Syria, Lebanon and northern Israel. It was introduced to Europe in the 16th century. It is widely cultivated everywhere in the temperate world for its strongly fragrant flowers which appear exceptionally early in the season, and frequently forced to flower at Christmas time.\",\r\n          \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyacinthus_orientalis\",\r\n          \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\",\r\n          \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"\r\n        },\r\n        \"taxonomy\": {\r\n          \"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\",\r\n          \"family\": \"Asparagaceae\",\r\n          \"genus\": \"Hyacinthus\",\r\n          \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\",\r\n          \"order\": \"Asparagales\",\r\n          \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"\r\n        },\r\n        \"synonyms\": [\r\n          \"Scilla coronaria\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"scientific_name\": \"Hyacinthus orientalis\",\r\n        \"structured_name\": {\r\n          \"genus\": \"hyacinthus\",\r\n          \"species\": \"orientalis\"\r\n        }\r\n      },\r\n      \"probability\": 0.016189891724569874,\r\n      \"confirmed\": false,\r\n      \"similar_images\": [\r\n        {\r\n          \"id\": \"f82116c027edfab963c3fbf0b090f320\",\r\n          \"similarity\": 0.30137169277972187,\r\n          \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/f82/116c027edfab963c3fbf0b090f320.jpg\",\r\n          \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/f82/116c027edfab963c3fbf0b090f320.small.jpg\"\r\n        },\r\n        {\r\n          \"id\": \"6f16f44a4d4fa2f8db18a5a539e53fd2\",\r\n          \"similarity\": 0.28263002581055663,\r\n          \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/6f1/6f44a4d4fa2f8db18a5a539e53fd2.jpg\",\r\n          \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/6f1/6f44a4d4fa2f8db18a5a539e53fd2.small.jpg\"\r\n        }\r\n      ]\r\n    },\r\n    {\r\n      \"id\": 234343031,\r\n      \"plant_name\": \"Dracaena angolensis\",\r\n      \"plant_details\": {\r\n        \"common_names\": [\r\n          \"cylindrical snake plant\",\r\n          \"African spear\",\r\n          \"spear sansevieria\",\r\n          \"Saint Bu00e1rbara sword\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dracaena_angolensis\",\r\n        \"name_authority\": \"Dracaena angolensis (Welw. ex Carriu00e8re) Byng & Christenh.\",\r\n        \"wiki_description\": {\r\n          \"value\": \"Dracaena angolensis, synonym Sansevieria cylindrica, also known as the cylindrical snake plant, African spear or spear sansevieria or in Brazil Saint Bu00e1rbara sword, is a succulent plant native to Angola.\",\r\n          \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dracaena_angolensis\",\r\n          \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\",\r\n          \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"\r\n        },\r\n        \"taxonomy\": {\r\n          \"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\",\r\n          \"family\": \"Asparagaceae\",\r\n          \"genus\": \"Dracaena\",\r\n          \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\",\r\n          \"order\": \"Asparagales\",\r\n          \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"\r\n        },\r\n        \"synonyms\": [\r\n          \"Acyntha cylindrica\",\r\n          \"Cordyline cylindrica\",\r\n          \"Sansevieria cylindrica\",\r\n          \"Sansevieria livingstoniae\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"scientific_name\": \"Dracaena angolensis\",\r\n        \"structured_name\": {\r\n          \"genus\": \"dracaena\",\r\n          \"species\": \"angolensis\"\r\n        }\r\n      },\r\n      \"probability\": 0.014439557355160414,\r\n      \"confirmed\": false,\r\n      \"similar_images\": [\r\n        {\r\n          \"id\": \"19457722bd87bdabbd696320768613c2\",\r\n          \"similarity\": 0.4042759633045478,\r\n          \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/194/57722bd87bdabbd696320768613c2.jpg\",\r\n          \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/194/57722bd87bdabbd696320768613c2.small.jpg\"\r\n        },\r\n        {\r\n          \"id\": \"c98a1e7184f2e0fa4df841557e8fa4ae\",\r\n          \"similarity\": 0.39013163547705065,\r\n          \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/c98/a1e7184f2e0fa4df841557e8fa4ae.jpg\",\r\n          \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/c98/a1e7184f2e0fa4df841557e8fa4ae.small.jpg\"\r\n        }\r\n      ]\r\n    },\r\n    {\r\n      \"id\": 234343032,\r\n      \"plant_name\": \"Epidendrum radicans\",\r\n      \"plant_details\": {\r\n        \"common_names\": [\r\n          \"ground-rooting epidendrum\",\r\n          \"fire-star orchid\",\r\n          \"rainbow orchid\",\r\n          \"reed-stem epidendrum\"\r\n        ],\r\n        \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidendrum_radicans\",\r\n        \"name_authority\": \"Epidendrum radicans Pav. ex Lindl.\",\r\n        \"wiki_description\": {\r\n          \"value\": \"Epidendrum radicans is a species of orchid. Common names include ground-rooting epidendrum, fire-star orchid, rainbow orchid, and reed-stem epidendrum. It is a common roadside weed at middle elevations in Central America. It is a crucifix orchid, often confused with many other members of the section Schistochila, including E. calanthe, E. cinnabarinum, E. denticulatum, E. erectum, E. fulgens, E. ibaguense, E. imatophy