g been in use in China for more than 3000 years.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diospyros_kaki\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"common_names\": [\"Oriental persimmon\", \"Chinese persimmon\", \"Japanese persimmon\", \"kaki persimmon\"], \"gbif_id\": \"3032984\", \"propagation_methods\": [\"cuttings\", \"grafting\", \"seeds\"], \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diospyros_kaki\", \"synonyms\": [\"Diospyros amara\", \"Diospyros argyi\", \"Diospyros bertii\", \"Diospyros chinensis\", \"Diospyros costata\", \"Diospyros kaempferi\", \"Diospyros lycopersicon\", \"Diospyros roxburghii\", \"Diospyros schi-tse\", \"Diospyros sinensis\", \"Diospyros sphenophylla\", \"Diospyros trichocarpa\", \"Diospyros wieseneri\", \"Embryopteris kaki\"], \"scientific_name\": \"Diospyros kaki\", \"structured_name\": {\"genus\": \"diospyros\", \"species\": \"kaki\"}}, \"probability\": 0.06333902438022591, \"confirmed\": false, \"similar_images\": [{\"id\": \"5a2548a99781a77f5433a2460446e0ff\", \"similarity\": 0.46676469303880913, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/5a2/548a99781a77f5433a2460446e0ff.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/5a2/548a99781a77f5433a2460446e0ff.small.jpg\"}, {\"id\": \"a0c477c520ae1a8a350d942c6bc52b7f\", \"similarity\": 0.34703479679215155, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/a0c/477c520ae1a8a350d942c6bc52b7f.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/a0c/477c520ae1a8a350d942c6bc52b7f.small.jpg\", \"citation\": \"Sphl\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 4.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/\"}]}, {\"id\": 234633628, \"plant_name\": \"Vicia faba\", \"plant_details\": {\"wiki_image\": {\"value\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/plant_id_knowledge_base/90b/822be66db5306c4bdf5d5464c11a9.jpg\", \"citation\": \"Bjoertvedt\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"edible_parts\": [\"flowers\", \"leaves\", \"seeds\"], \"taxonomy\": {\"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\", \"family\": \"Fabaceae\", \"genus\": \"Vicia\", \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\", \"order\": \"Fabales\", \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"}, \"name_authority\": \"Vicia faba L.\", \"wiki_description\": {\"value\": \"Vicia faba, also known in the culinary sense as the broad bean, fava bean, or faba bean, is a species of flowering plant in the pea and bean family Fabaceae. It is of uncertain origin and widely cultivated as a crop for human consumption. It is also used as a cover crop. Varieties with smaller, harder seeds that are fed to horses or other animals are called field bean, tic bean or tick bean. Horse bean, Vicia faba var. equina Pers., is a variety recognized as an accepted name.\\nSome people suffer from favism, a hemolytic response to the consumption of broad beans, a condition linked to a metabolism disorder known as G6PDD. Otherwise the beans, with the outer seed coat removed, can be eaten raw or cooked. In young plants, the outer seed coat can be eaten, and in very young plants, the seed pod can be eaten.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vicia_faba\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"common_names\": [\"broad bean\", \"fava bean\", \"field bean\", \"tic bean\", \"Horse bean\"], \"gbif_id\": \"2974832\", \"propagation_methods\": [\"seeds\"], \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vicia_faba\", \"synonyms\": [\"Faba bona subsp. equina\", \"Faba equina\", \"Faba faba\", \"Faba major\", \"Faba minor\", \"Faba sativa\", \"Faba vulgaris\", \"Faba vulgaris subsp. minor\", \"Orobus faba\", \"Vicia equina\", \"Vicia esculenta\", \"Vicia faba var. minor\", \"Vicia pliniana\", \"Vicia porphyrea\", \"Vicia vulgaris\"], \"scientific_name\": \"Vicia faba\", \"structured_name\": {\"genus\": \"vicia\", \"species\": \"faba\"}}, \"probability\": 0.04874450008912801, \"confirmed\": false, \"similar_images\": [{\"id\": \"4fd5aea83fca739ac28dcd68cecbe844\", \"similarity\": 0.5092965956504797, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/4fd/5aea83fca739ac28dcd68cecbe844.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/4fd/5aea83fca739ac28dcd68cecbe844.small.jpg\", \"citation\": \"Bodhi Peace\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 4.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/\"}, {\"id\": \"813c3c88b45c7211469be139ade5bda1\", \"similarity\": 0.08789517581008273, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/813/c3c88b45c7211469be139ade5bda1.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/813/c3c88b45c7211469be139ade5bda1.small.jpg\"}]}, {\"id\": 234633629, \"plant_name\": \"Pyrus pyrifolia\", \"plant_details\": {\"wiki_image\": {\"value\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/plant_id_knowledge_base/ca1/517a7ba47129e16aec742911f4f05.jpg\", \"citation\": null, \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 4.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/\"}, \"edible_parts\": null, \"taxonomy\": {\"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\", \"family\": \"Rosaceae\", \"genus\": \"Pyrus\", \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\", \"order\": \"Rosales\", \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"}, \"name_authority\": \"Pyrus pyrifolia (Burm.f.) Nakai\", \"wiki_description\": {\"value\": \"Pyrus pyrifolia is a species of pear tree native to East Asia. The tree\'s edible fruit is known by many names, including: Asian pear, Japanese pear, Chinese pear, Korean pear, Taiwanese pear, apple pear, zodiac pear, three-halves pear, papple and sand pear. Along with cultivars of P. \\u00d7 bretschneideri and P. ussuriensis, the fruit is also called the nashi pear. Cultivars derived from Pyrus pyrifolia are grown throughout East Asia, and in other countries such as India, Australia, New Zealand, and the United States (e.g., California). Traditionally in East Asia the tree\'s flowers are a popular symbol of early spring, and it is a common sight in gardens and the countryside.\\nThe fruits are not generally baked in pies or made into jams because they have a high water content and a crisp, grainy texture, very different from the European varieties. They are commonly served raw and peeled. The fruit tends to be quite large and fragrant, and when carefully wrapped (it has a tendency to bruise because of its juiciness), it can last for several weeks or more in a cold, dry place.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyrus_pyrifolia\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"common_names\": [\"Asian pear\", \"Japanese pear\", \"Chinese pear\", \"Korean pear\", \"Taiwanese pear\", \"apple pear\", \"zodiac pear\", \"papple\", \"sand pear\", \"nashi pear\"], \"gbif_id\": \"5362786\", \"propagation_methods\": null, \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyrus_pyrifolia\", \"synonyms\": [\"Ficus pyrifolia\", \"Pyrus arakiana\", \"Pyrus asakeensis\", \"Pyrus autumnalis\", \"Pyrus babauttiagi\", \"Pyrus cuneata\", \"Pyrus higoensis\", \"Pyrus incubacea\", \"Pyrus kiushiana\", \"Pyrus kleinhofiana\", \"Pyrus lakuhokuensis\", \"Pyrus lasiogyna\", \"Pyrus lindleyi\", \"Pyrus nehiyamadonis\", \"Pyrus pseudocalleryana\", \"Pyrus pseudouipongensis\", \"Pyrus pyrifolia var. talyschensis\", \"Pyrus saidaeana\", \"Pyrus serotina\", \"Pyrus sinensis\", \"Pyrus sohayakiensis\", \"Pyrus tajimaensis\", \"Pyrus tambana\", \"Pyrus tobisimensis\", \"Pyrus togashiana\", \"Pyrus tsuchiyana\", \"Pyrus tungusiana\", \"Pyrus uipongensis\", \"Pyrus umemurana\", \"Pyrus uyematsuana\", \"Pyrus yohrohensis\"], \"scientifi