 or culinary apple. The other species are commonly known as crabapples, crab apples, crabtrees, or wild apples.\\nThe genus is native to the temperate zone of the Northern Hemisphere.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malus\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"common_names\": [\"crabapple\", \"the Apples\", \"orchard apple\", \"eating apple\", \"cooking apple\", \"culinary apple\", \"crabtrees\", \"wild apples\"], \"gbif_id\": \"3001068\", \"propagation_methods\": null, \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malus\", \"synonyms\": [\"Chloromeles\", \"Sinomalus\", \"\\u00d7 Tormimalus\"], \"scientific_name\": \"Malus\", \"structured_name\": {\"genus\": \"malus\"}}, \"probability\": 0.029862332841839815, \"confirmed\": false, \"similar_images\": [{\"id\": \"d626160a0d449ab51d547cef3a0d6e1e\", \"similarity\": 0.45639867561654435, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/d62/6160a0d449ab51d547cef3a0d6e1e.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/d62/6160a0d449ab51d547cef3a0d6e1e.small.jpg\"}, {\"id\": \"c326d802daff4aa61ec08f1b83cd8b85\", \"similarity\": 0.28537171527517535, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/c32/6d802daff4aa61ec08f1b83cd8b85.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/c32/6d802daff4aa61ec08f1b83cd8b85.small.jpg\"}]}, {\"id\": 234633631, \"plant_name\": \"Malus domestica\", \"plant_details\": {\"wiki_image\": {\"value\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/plant_id_knowledge_base/5a1/f0a509446a2ddec6878f5ec311ed3.jpg\", \"citation\": \"Bob Balmer\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY 2.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\"}, \"edible_parts\": [\"fruit\"], \"taxonomy\": {\"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\", \"family\": \"Rosaceae\", \"genus\": \"Malus\", \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\", \"order\": \"Rosales\", \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"}, \"name_authority\": \"Malus domestica (Suckow) Borkh.\", \"wiki_description\": {\"value\": \"An apple is an edible fruit produced by an apple tree (Malus domestica). Apple trees are cultivated worldwide and are the most widely grown species in the genus Malus. The tree originated in Central Asia, where its wild ancestor, Malus sieversii, is still found today. Apples have been grown for thousands of years in Asia and Europe and were brought to North America by European colonists. Apples have religious and mythological significance in many cultures, including Norse, Greek, and European Christian tradition.\\nApple trees are large if grown from seed. Generally, apple cultivars are propagated by grafting onto rootstocks, which control the size of the resulting tree. There are more than 7,500 known cultivars of apples, resulting in a range of desired characteristics. Different cultivars are bred for various tastes and use, including cooking, eating raw and cider production. Trees and fruit are prone to a number of fungal, bacterial and pest problems, which can be controlled by a number of organic and non-organic means. In 2010, the fruit\'s genome was sequenced as part of research on disease control and selective breeding in apple production.\\nWorldwide production of apples in 2018 was 86 million tonnes, with China accounting for nearly half of the total.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malus_domestica\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"common_names\": [\"apple\", \"apple tree\"], \"gbif_id\": \"3001244\", \"propagation_methods\": [\"seeds\", \"suckers\"], \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malus_domestica\", \"synonyms\": [\"Malus anisophylla\", \"Malus apetala\", \"Malus astracanica\", \"Malus batavica\", \"Malus chitralensis\", \"Malus communis\", \"Malus cylindracea\", \"Malus