mmon name but are not related to true lilies.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lilium\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"taxonomy\": {\"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\", \"family\": \"Liliaceae\", \"genus\": \"Lilium\", \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\", \"order\": \"Liliales\", \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"}, \"synonyms\": [\"Lirium\", \"Martagon\", \"Nomocharis\"], \"scientific_name\": \"Lilium\", \"structured_name\": {\"genus\": \"lilium\"}}, \"probability\": 0.07790943662460062, \"confirmed\": false, \"similar_images\": [{\"id\": \"18602144b9569010ae8c8201fa5bfe91\", \"similarity\": 0.2528319628732301, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/186/02144b9569010ae8c8201fa5bfe91.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/186/02144b9569010ae8c8201fa5bfe91.small.jpg\"}, {\"id\": \"945584f1779c91225c1fd59a53275514\", \"similarity\": 0.22592089474807847, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/945/584f1779c91225c1fd59a53275514.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/945/584f1779c91225c1fd59a53275514.small.jpg\"}]}, {\"id\": 234637443, \"plant_name\": \"Aloe vera\", \"plant_details\": {\"common_names\": [\"Barbados aloe\", \"burn plant\", \"coastal aloe\", \"common aloe\", \"Cura\\u00e7ao aloe\", \"Indian aloe\", \"Jaffarabad aloe\", \"medicinal aloe\", \"Mediterranean aloe\", \"true aloe\", \"West Indian aloe\", \"Bitter Aloes\", \"Medicine Plant\"], \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aloe_vera\", \"name_authority\": \"Aloe vera (L.) Burm.f.\", \"wiki_description\": {\"value\": \"Aloe vera ( or ) is a succulent plant species of the genus Aloe. An evergreen perennial, it originates from the Arabian Peninsula, but grows wild in tropical, semi-tropical, and arid climates around the world. It is cultivated for agricultural and medicinal uses. The species is also used for decorative purposes and grows successfully indoors as a potted plant.\\nIt is found in many consumer products including beverages, skin lotion, cosmetics, ointments or in the form of gel for minor burns and sunburns. There is little clinical evidence for the effectiveness or safety of Aloe vera extract as a cosmetic or medicine.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aloe_vera\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"taxonomy\": {\"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\", \"family\": \"Asphodelaceae\", \"genus\": \"Aloe\", \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\", \"order\": \"Asparagales\", \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"}, \"synonyms\": [\"Aloe barbadensis\", \"Aloe chinensis\", \"Aloe elongata\", \"Aloe flava\", \"Aloe indica\", \"Aloe lanzae\", \"Aloe maculata\", \"Aloe perfoliata var. barbadensis\", \"Aloe perfoliata var. vera\", \"Aloe rubescens\", \"Aloe variegata\", \"Aloe vera var. littoralis\", \"Aloe vulgaris\"], \"scientific_name\": \"Aloe vera\", \"structured_name\": {\"genus\": \"aloe\", \"species\": \"vera\"}}, \"probability\": 0.07072626543469629, \"confirmed\": false, \"similar_images\": [{\"id\": \"4f496a629d590582373f14cdba5dafdd\", \"similarity\": 0.4244141264722988, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/4f4/96a629d590582373f14cdba5dafdd.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/4f4/96a629d590582373f14cdba5dafdd.small.jpg\"}, {\"id\": \"692aec3ac0d042327ee7d98e5d22103c\", \"similarity\": 0.30187232971157885, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/692/aec3ac0d042327ee7d98e5d22103c.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/692/aec3ac0d042327ee7d98e5d22103c.small.jpg\"}]}, {\"id\": 234637444, \"plant_name\": \"Dracaena sanderiana\", \"plant_details\": {\"common_names\": [\"Ribbon Dracaena\", \"Lucky Bamboo\", \"Belgian Evergreen\", \"Ribbon Plant\"], \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dracaena_sanderiana\", \"name_authority\": \"Dracaena sanderiana Mast.\", \"wiki_description\": {\"value\": \"Dracaena sanderiana is a species of flowering plant in the family Asparagaceae, native to Central Africa. It was named after the German\\u2013English gardener Henry Frederick Conrad Sander (1847\\u20131920). The plant is commonly marketed as \\\"lucky bamboo\\\". The plant has become the most popular indoor plant in certain parts of India, where the plants are usually imported from China and Taiwan.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dracaena_sanderiana\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"taxonomy\": {\"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\", \"family\": \"Asparagaceae\", \"genus\": \"Dracaena\", \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\", \"order\": \"Asparagales\", \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"}, \"synonyms\": [\"Dracaena poggei\", \"Dracaena vanderystii\", \"Pleomele poggei\", \"Pleomele sanderiana\"], \"scientific_name\": \"Dracaena sanderiana\", \"structured_name\": {\"genus\": \"dracaena\", \"species\": \"sanderiana\"}}, \"probability\": 0.03933697812322083, \"confirmed\": false, \"similar_images\": [{\"id\": \"f7fd9a9bb7fc0cbc8f85460e8143bebb\", \"similarity\": 0.297031329320089, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/f7f/d9a9bb7fc0cbc8f85460e8143bebb.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/f7f/d9a9bb7fc0cbc8f85460e8143bebb.small.jpg\", \"citation\": \"Toby Lee Spiegel\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY 2.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/\"}, {\"id\": \"a273b341b6564b5522a7ed3b862e4be4\", \"similarity\": 0.16136063459737554, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/a27/3b341b6564b5522a7ed3b862e4be4.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/a27/3b341b6564b5522a7ed3b862e4be4.small.jpg\"}]}, {\"id\": 234637445, \"plant_name\": \"Allium fistulosum\", \"plant_details\": {\"common_names\": [\"Welsh onion\", \"bunching onion\", \"green onion\", \"long green onion\", \"Japanese bunching onion\", \"spring onion\"], \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allium_fistulosum\", \"name_authority\": \"Allium fistulosum L.\", \"wiki_description\": {\"value\": \"Allium fistulosum, the Welsh onion, also commonly called bunching onion, long green onion, Japanese bunching onion, and spring onion, is a species of perennial plant, often considered to be a kind of scallion.\\nThe species is very similar in taste and odor to the related common onion, Allium cepa, and hybrids between the two (tree onions) exist. A. fistulosum, however, does not develop bulbs, and possesses hollow leaves (fistulosum means \\\"hollow\\\") and scapes. Larger varieties of the A. fistulosum resemble the leek, such as the Japanese negi, whilst smaller varieties resemble chives. A. fistulosum can multiply by forming perennial evergreen clumps. It is also grown in a bunch as an ornamental plant.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allium_fistulosum\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"taxonomy\": {\"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\", \"family\": \"Amaryllidaceae\", \"genus\": \"Allium\", \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\", \"order\": \"Asparagales\", \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"}, \"synonyms\": [\"Allium bouddae\", \"Allium kashgaricum\", \"Cepa fissilis\", \"Cepa fistulosa\", \"Cepa ventricosa\", \"Kepa fistulosa\", \"Phyllodolon fistulosum\", \"Porrum fistulosum\"], \"scientific_name\": \"Allium fistulosum\", \"structured_name\": {\"genus\": \"allium\", \"species\": \"fistulosum\"}}, \"probability\": 0.03688405608686612, \"confirmed\": false, \"similar_images\": [{\"id\": \"a77a8687f6b52abf887f054baf3daa49\", \"similarity\": 0.3662875081084549, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/a77/a8687f6b52abf887f054baf3daa49.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/a77/a8687f6b52abf887f054baf3daa49.small.jpg\"}, {\"id\": \"3dee9dcef7c82f16068ae96e232c8378\", \"similarity\": 0.15926277607004458, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/3de/e9dcef7c82f16068ae96e232c8378.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/3de/e9dcef7c82f16068ae96e232c8378.small.jpg\", \"citation\": \"Jan S\\u00f8rensen\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY 4.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/\"}]}, {\"id\": 234637446, \"plant_name\": \"Narcissus\", \"plant_details\": {\"common_names\": [\"daffodil\", \"jonquil\"], \"url\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narcissus_(plant)\", \"name_authority\": \"Narcissus L.\", \"wiki_description\": {\"value\": \"Narcissus is a genus of predominantly spring flowering perennial plants of the amaryllis family, Amaryllidaceae. Various common names including daffodil, narcissus and jonquil are used to describe all or some members of the genus. Narcissus has conspicuous flowers with six petal-like tepals surmounted by a cup- or trumpet-shaped corona. The flowers are generally white or yellow (also orange or pink in garden varieties), with either uniform or contrasting coloured tepals and corona.\\nNarcissus were well known in ancient civilisation, both medicinally and botanically, but formally described by Linnaeus in his Species Plantarum (1753). The genus is generally considered to have about ten sections with approximately 50 species. The number of species has varied, depending on how they are classified, due to similarity between species and hybridisation. The genus arose some time in the Late Oligocene to Early Miocene epochs, in the Iberian peninsula and adjacent areas of southwest Europe. The exact origin of the name Narcissus is unknown, but it is often linked to a Greek word for intoxicated (narcotic) and the myth of the youth of that name who fell in love with his own reflection. The English word \\\"daffodil\\\" appears to be derived from \\\"asphodel\\\", with which it was commonly compared.\\nThe species are native to meadows and woods in southern Europe and North Africa with a centre of diversity in the Western Mediterranean, particularly the Iberian peninsula. Both wild and cultivated plants have naturalised widely, and were introduced into the Far East prior to the tenth century. Narcissi tend to be long-lived bulbs, which propagate by division, but are also insect-pollinated. Known pests, diseases and disorders include viruses, fungi, the larvae of flies, mites and nematodes. Some Narcissus species have become extinct, while others are threatened by increasing urbanisation and tourism.\\nHistorical accounts suggest narcissi have been cultivated from the earliest times, but became increasingly popular in Europe after the 16th century and by the late 19th century were an important commercial crop centred primarily in the Netherlands. Today narcissi are popular as cut flowers and as ornamental plants in private and public gardens. The long history of breeding has resulted in thousands of different cultivars. For horticultural purposes, narcissi are classified into divisions, covering a wide range of shapes and colours. Like other members of their family, narcissi produce a number of different alkaloids, which provide some protection for the plant, but may be poisonous if accidentally ingested. This property has been exploited for medicinal use in traditional healing and has resulted in the production of galantamine for the treatment of Alzheimer\'s dementia. Long celebrated in art and literature, narcissi are associated with a number of themes in different cultures, ranging from death to good fortune, and as symbols of spring. The daffodil is the national flower of Wales and the symbol of cancer charities in many countries. The appearance of the wild flowers in spring is associated with festivals in many places.\", \"citation\": \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narcissus_(plant)\", \"license_name\": \"CC BY-SA 3.0\", \"license_url\": \"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/\"}, \"taxonomy\": {\"class\": \"Magnoliopsida\", \"family\": \"Amaryllidaceae\", \"genus\": \"Narcissus\", \"kingdom\": \"Plantae\", \"order\": \"Asparagales\", \"phylum\": \"Magnoliophyta\"}, \"synonyms\": [\"Ajax\", \"Argenope\", \"Assaracus\", \"Aurelia\", \"Autogenes\", \"Braxireon\", \"Calathinus\", \"Carregnoa\", \"Chione\", \"Chloraster\", \"Codiaminum\", \"Corbularia\", \"Cydenis\", \"Diomedes\", \"Ganymedes\", \"Gymnoterpe\", \"Helena\", \"Hermione\", \"Illus\", \"Jonquilla\", \"Moskerion\", \"Oileus\", \"Panza\", \"Patrocles\", \"Philogyne\", \"Phylogyne\", \"Plateana\", \"Prasiteles\", \"Queltia\", \"Schisanthes\", \"Stephanophorum\", \"Tapeinaegle\", \"Tapeinanthus\", \"Tityrus\", \"Tros\", \"Veniera\", \"\\u00d7 Narcibularia\"], \"scientific_name\": \"Narcissus\", \"structured_name\": {\"genus\": \"narcissus\"}}, \"probability\": 0.024087714861157787, \"confirmed\": false, \"similar_images\": [{\"id\": \"224257d4be9f982e8462b4a6438389a8\", \"similarity\": 0.26959919103864893, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/224/257d4be9f982e8462b4a6438389a8.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/224/257d4be9f982e8462b4a6438389a8.small.jpg\"}, {\"id\": \"55170d648a762be75648fdfaab896917\", \"similarity\": 0.17466023284879884, \"url\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/551/70d648a762be75648fdfaab896917.jpg\", \"url_small\": \"https://plant-id.ams3.cdn.digitaloceanspaces.com/similar_images/images/551/70d648a762be756